1775838697588324	bones-dev	itc:v3:AWKSZJkkk5JkmZMxAAAAQatWqrq1bWwAAAE3mQw		item.comment	bn-1vyj	{"body":"Closing as not warranted. After bn-pu4y + bn-3f00 + bn-30ub landed, the measured hot paths (pagerank, normalize, full_rebuild) are all now dominated by their algorithmic rewrites, not by allocation or hash-map overhead. The bn-2ury baseline + re-measurements do not show query-path allocations as a hot spot anywhere. Surgical SmallVec/ahash swaps require a visible allocation/hash signal in a flamegraph before they're worth doing; without that, the change would be speculative optimization that contradicts the measurement-driven discipline this pass is following. Reopen only if a future flamegraph (scripts/flamegraph.sh) shows allocator or HashMap::insert high on a bn search / bn triage profile."}	blake3:BId2K5wBTF0pS4yZjmk__nOy00GUz8k1qMf7J5rh6Fs
1775838703978945	bones-dev	itc:v3:AWKSZJkkk5JkmZMxAAAAQatWqrq1bWwAAAE3mgw		item.comment	bn-125x	{"body":"Closing as not warranted. The bn-17xg measurement showed TUI RSS is extremely stable under the system allocator (4.8 MB → 6.0 MB over 500 render cycles + 500 detail cycles + 5000 markdown renders + 500 full tick cycles, total growth 1.2 MB). Per-Issue String allocations are not on the hot path. The u16-offset packing pattern would save memory only if String allocations were visible in a dhat profile — they are not. bn-3mqr tracks the real TUI memory investigation (ORT semantic-search model state), which is where the 1.6 GB RSS actually lives. Reopen only if dhat-heap shows Issue-struct string allocations as a top consumer."}	blake3:vp6Rytp8uGHZizYHoXhZWg_pa_dhPfEsjLuFPMzVTyk
1775838710295986	bones-dev	itc:v3:AWKSZJkkk5JkmZMxAAAAQatWqrq1bWwAAAE3mww		item.comment	bn-1q3k	{"body":"Closing as superseded. bn-1ylg already swapped the TUI list sorts from stable sort_by to sort_unstable_by (verified safe because every comparator tie-breaks on item_id). The bn-2ury baseline showed list_open_items/M is 789 µs end-to-end for 10 000 items, well under the 200 ms SLO — sort is not a hot path on realistic workloads. glidesort's advantage is on nearly-sorted inputs; even if it gave 10-20 %, that would be a sub-microsecond win against a 200 ms budget. The effort/payoff ratio is upside-down. Reopen only if a TUI scenario emerges where sort actually shows in a flamegraph."}	blake3:qt_2g8XXBRcW5COK_-i8gNDrl8TP_vJqjgvxDccPpLc
